{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17630073","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17630073"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:12:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:12:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17302"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17302","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17302"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.03,0.07,0.57,0.33]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9992"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71623"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9992","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9992"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17302"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57119"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5325"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23405"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23407"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23510"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71623","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71623"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after a fall onto his right elbow. He is found to have a fracture of the medial epicondyle. The patient cannot flex his wrist and reports numbness in his palm and the palmar aspect of the lateral three and a half digits, including the nail beds. Neurological examination reveals weakness in wrist flexion and decreased sensation in the affected areas.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following nerves is most likely injured?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Axillary","Musculocutaneous","Radial","Median","Ulnar"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation is consistent with an injury to the \u003Cstrong\u003Emedian nerve\u003C/strong\u003E. The median nerve is responsible for wrist flexion and provides sensation to the palm and the palmar aspect of the lateral three and a half digits, including the nail beds. Injury to this nerve can result in the inability to flex the wrist and sensory deficits in these areas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eaxillary nerve\u003C/strong\u003E primarily innervates the deltoid and teres minor muscles and provides sensation to the skin over the deltoid. It is not involved in wrist flexion or sensation of the hand.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emusculocutaneous nerve\u003C/strong\u003E innervates the muscles of the anterior compartment of the arm and provides sensation to the lateral forearm. It does not affect wrist flexion or hand sensation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eradial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is responsible for extension of the wrist and fingers and provides sensation to the posterior aspect of the arm and hand. It does not affect wrist flexion or the palmar aspect of the hand.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eulnar nerve\u003C/strong\u003E innervates the intrinsic muscles of the hand and provides sensation to the medial one and a half digits. It does not affect wrist flexion or the lateral aspect of the hand.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The median nerve is responsible for wrist flexion and sensation of the palm and palmar aspect of the lateral 3.5 digits.","Injury to the median nerve can result in loss of wrist flexion and sensory deficits in the hand."],"references":["Polcaro L, Charlick M, Daly DT. Anatomy, Head and Neck: Brachial Plexus. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK531473/","Sakellariou VI, Badilas NK, Mazis GA, Stavropoulos NA, Kotoulas HK, Kyriakopoulos S, Tagkalegkas I, Sofianos IP. Brachial plexus injuries in adults: evaluation and diagnostic approach. ISRN Orthop. 2014 Feb 9;2014:726103. doi: 10.1155/2014/726103. PMID: 24967130; PMCID: PMC4045362","Howard, R., Kullmann, D., Werring, D., \u0026 Zandi, M. (Eds.). (2024). Neurology: a queen square textbook. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57119"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17302"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57119","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57119"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-19T20:40:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-19T20:40:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9992"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71623"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"crea